ciscoLwappIpv6MIB.name: ciscoLwappIpv6MIB
ciscoLwappIpv6MIB.contactinfo: Cisco Systems, Customer Service Postal: 170 West Tasman Drive San Jose, CA 95134 USA Tel: +1 800 553-NETS Email: cs-wnbu-snmp@cisco.com
ciscoLwappIpv6MIB.description: This MIB is intended to be implemented on all those devices operating as Central Controllers (CC) that terminate the Light Weight Access Point Protocol tunnel from Light-weight LWAPP Access Points. This MIB provides configuration and status information about the ACLs on the controller. Particularly this mib covers the CPU ACLs for the wireless controllers. Traffic to the controller CPU comes from the NPU (Network Processing Unit). Using CPU ACLs, the user can place restrictions on type of traffic reaching the CPU of the controller from the NPU. CPU ACLs introduce an ACL for the traffic to the CPU of controller. With this ACL the type of packets reaching the CPU can be controlled. The mode of operation is as follows. The administrator designates one ACL for the traffic to the CPU. The ACL kicks in for packets from the NPU to the CPU. Each ACL is an ordered set of rules. If a rule matches then action for that rule is applied to the packet. The decision to send or drop the packet is taken based on the action parameter of the ACL. There will be no ACL for the packets from the CPU to the NPU. GLOSSARY Access Control List ( ACL ) A list of rules used to restrict the traffic reaching an interface or the CPU. Each ACL is an ordered set of rules and actions. If a rule matches then the action for that rule is applied to the packet. Access Point ( AP ) An entity that contains an 802.11 medium access control ( MAC ) and physical layer ( PHY ) interface and provides acess to the distribution services via the wireless medium for associated clients. CPU ACL ( CPU ACL ) The ACL applied to the CPU. This controls the type of traffic reaching the CPU of the controller. Network Processing Unit ( NPU ) This entity is responsible for forwarding traffic to the CPU. The only exceptions are data coming thorugh the console port and the Service port i.e. these communicate directly with the CPU and not via the NPU. Light Weight Access Point Protocol ( LWAPP ) This is a generic protocol that defines the communciation between the Access Points and the Central Controller. Cryptographically Generated Addresses (CGA) Cryptographically Generated Addresses (CGAs) are IPv6 addresses, which allow for a secure association of an IPv6 address, the CGA, with a public key. REFERENCE [1] Part 11 Wireless LAN Medium Access Control ( MAC ) and Physical Layer ( PHY ) Specifications.

cLIpv6AclTable.name: cLIpv6AclTable
cLIpv6AclTable.description: The table listing IPv6 ACLs (Access Control Lists) on the Switch.

cLIpv6AclEntry.name: cLIpv6AclEntry
cLIpv6AclEntry.description: Each entry in this table provides information about one IPv6 ACL of the controller.

cLIpv6AclName.name: cLIpv6AclName
cLIpv6AclName.description: Name of the Access Control List.

cLIpv6AclApplyMode.name: cLIpv6AclApplyMode
cLIpv6AclApplyMode.description: The apply mode of the ACL on the switch. Mode value 'applied' means the ACL has been applied on the switch.

cLIpv6AclCounterClear.name: cLIpv6AclCounterClear
cLIpv6AclCounterClear.description: This object when set to 'true', will clear the counter of the ACL represented by the unique ACL name.

cLIpv6AclRowStatus.name: cLIpv6AclRowStatus
cLIpv6AclRowStatus.description: Row Status of the IPv6 ACL. Modification of row is possible.

cLIpv6AclRuleTable.name: cLIpv6AclRuleTable
cLIpv6AclRuleTable.description: The table listing Acl Rules(Access Control List Entries) on the ACL with name cLIpv6AclName.

cLIpv6AclRuleIndex.name: cLIpv6AclRuleIndex
cLIpv6AclRuleIndex.description: Index of the ACL rule. This can be updated to reset the sequence of the rules of an ACL.

cLIpv6AclRuleAction.name: cLIpv6AclRuleAction
cLIpv6AclRuleAction.description: The permission mode of a rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleDirection.name: cLIpv6AclRuleDirection
cLIpv6AclRuleDirection.description: The direction of the packet to which the rule may be applied.

cLIpv6AclRuleSourceInetAddressType.name: cLIpv6AclRuleSourceInetAddressType
cLIpv6AclRuleSourceInetAddressType.description: Source Inet Address type of the ACL rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleSourceInetAddress.name: cLIpv6AclRuleSourceInetAddress
cLIpv6AclRuleSourceInetAddress.description: Source Inet Address of the ACL rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleSourcePrefixLength.name: cLIpv6AclRuleSourcePrefixLength
cLIpv6AclRuleSourcePrefixLength.description: This object denotes the prefix length for Source Inet address of the ACL rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationInetAddressType.name: cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationInetAddressType
cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationInetAddressType.description: Destination Inet Address type of the ACL rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationInetAddress.name: cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationInetAddress
cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationInetAddress.description: Destination Inet Address of the ACL rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationPrefixLength.name: cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationPrefixLength
cLIpv6AclRuleDestinationPrefixLength.description: This object denotes the prefix length for Destination Inet address of the ACL rule.

cLIpv6AclRuleProtocol.name: cLIpv6AclRuleProtocol
cLIpv6AclRuleProtocol.description: Protocol of the packet. It can be either of the pre specified protocols like TCP, UDP, ICMP, ESP, AH, GRE, IP, Ethernet Over IP, OSPF or any number between 0 and 255. A value 256 implies that this rule applies to 'Any' protocol.

cLIpv6AclRuleStartSourcePort.name: cLIpv6AclRuleStartSourcePort
cLIpv6AclRuleStartSourcePort.description: This object represents the start Source Port of the packet. It can be either of the pre specified ports like HTTP, HTTPS, Telnet, RADIUS etc or any number between 0 and 65535. A value 65536 implies that this rule applies to 'Any' source port. This value can be set only if the protocol is set to TCP or UDP. Otherwise the value is set to Any(65536)

cLIpv6AclRuleEndSourcePort.name: cLIpv6AclRuleEndSourcePort
cLIpv6AclRuleEndSourcePort.description: This object represents the end Source Port of the packet. It can be either of the pre specified ports like HTTP, HTTPS, Telnet, RADIUS etc or any number between 0 and 65535. A value 65536 implies that this rule applies to 'Any' source port. This value can be set only if the protocol is set to TCP or UDP. Otherwise the value is set to Any(65536)

cLIpv6AclRuleStartDestinationPort.name: cLIpv6AclRuleStartDestinationPort
cLIpv6AclRuleStartDestinationPort.description: This object represents the start Destination Port of the packet. It can be either of the pre specified ports like HTTP, HTTPS, Telnet, RADIUS etc or any number between 0 and 65535. A value 65536 implies that this rule aplpies to 'Any' Destination port. This value can be set only if the protocol is set to TCP or UDP. Otherwise the value is set to Any(65536)

cLIpv6AclRuleEndDestinationPort.name: cLIpv6AclRuleEndDestinationPort
cLIpv6AclRuleEndDestinationPort.description: This object represents the End Destination Port of the packet. It can be either of the pre specified ports like HTTP, HTTPS, Telnet, RADIUS etc or any number between 0 and 65535. A value 65536 implies that this rule aplpies to 'Any' Destination port. This value can be set only if the protocol is set to TCP or UDP. Otherwise the value is set to Any(65536)

cLIpv6AclRuleDscp.name: cLIpv6AclRuleDscp
cLIpv6AclRuleDscp.description: DSCP value of the rule. A value 256 implies Any

cLIpv6AclNewRuleIndex.name: cLIpv6AclNewRuleIndex
cLIpv6AclNewRuleIndex.description: New Index of the ACL rule. This attribute should be updated if the requirement is to reset the sequence of the rules of an ACL. A read on this will not yield anything.

cLIpv6AclRuleHits.name: cLIpv6AclRuleHits
cLIpv6AclRuleHits.description: Number of hits in the particular rule under the ACL.This object is cleared by setting the cLIpv6AclCounterClear object.

cLIpv6AclRuleRowStatus.name: cLIpv6AclRuleRowStatus
cLIpv6AclRuleRowStatus.description: Row Status of the ACL Rule.
